@vitordelima I would never try to argue that the iPhone was not revolutionary, both technologically and culturally. It clearly was.  But it has been easily duplicated in both form and function over time. It's capabilities are still ahead of the curve, to be sure, but not in any way that is important to average user.  The time it takes to duplicate its latest generation is shrinking, with some Android phones  having component specs that exceed an iPhone's upon its release. 

Jobs was a genius in aesthetics. He captured the imagination of 2 generations and counting. I'm not hating on Apple. I've owned and enjoyed iPods, iPads, and 1 iPhone.  They were all great products. More to the point of Robert's video, is to ask what can today's iPhone actually do better than any other phone that is both measureable AND meaningful. Jobs's genius is that he was able to take what could could be measured, place it in a unique form factor, and imbue it with meaning.

The only thing that separates the 2 today, in  my opinion, is that you will rarely find an Android user waiting in line (sometimes overnight) to buy the latest and greatest, defending to death the decision to spend, in some cases, nearly twice as much for decrementing gains.

